President Obama announced the expansion of the "Educate to Innovate" campaign, which aims to improve science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM) education in the United States. The campaign will receive over $250 million in public and private investments to train over 10,000 new math and science teachers and provide professional development for over 100,000 current teachers. The President also honored over 100 outstanding educators in STEM fields with the Presidential Award for Excellence in Teaching and Mentoring. The announcement included partnerships with major companies, universities, foundations, non-profit organizations, and government agencies to attract, develop, reward, and retain outstanding STEM educators. The partnerships will build upon programs previously announced by the President in November. The article also provides information on the background of the Presidential Awards and highlights other initiatives aimed at improving STEM education, including programs by Intel, UTeach, public universities, PBS, and the Woodrow Wilson Foundation. The article emphasizes the importance of quality STEM teachers in ensuring student success and preparing them for the challenges of the 21st century.